  "text": "Of 144 cases, 123 (85.4%) underwent comprehensive neuropsychological testing at a median of 25.3 weeks (IQR 35.4 weeks) prior to death. Seven domains of neurocognitive functioning were assessed: information processing speed, attention/working memory, learning, delayed recall, verbal fluency, abstraction/executive functioning, and motor/psychomotor speed, with statistical correction for demographic variables (i.e., age, sex, ethnicity, and education) [CITATION_1] . Both the number and severity of deficits across the neuropsychological battery were considered. A clinical diagnosis of HAND was made according to standard criteria requiring at least mild impairment of at least two domains of neurocognitive functioning [CITATION_2] . The neurocognitive diagnoses were distributed as follows: normal cognition (n ¼ 28, 22.8% of 123 cases), ANI (n ¼ 11, 8.9%), MND (n ¼ 16, 13.0%), and HAD (n ¼ 13, 10.6%). Also, there were 40 patients (32.5%) having neuropsychological impairment due to other causes (such as severe neurological comorbidities that could not be ruled out as the primary cause of any neurocognitive impairment) and 15 patients (12.2%) whose diagnoses were inconclusive based on insufficient data; these patients were excluded from statistical analysis.",
